ref: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.304, Issue.1, p.210 (1978)
title: The 18O(p,alpha)15N cross section at low energies

x4freetext: The 18O(p,alpha)15N cross section at low energies

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.304, Issue.1, p.210 (1978)

x4freetext: Al2O3 target enriched in 18O (>90% of 18O) were
produced by evaporating aluminum oxide onto 7
microgram/cm2 carbon foils on glass slides.
Five silicon surface-barrier detectors were
used in the measurement. A detector at theta=157
degrees was used to monitor the incident beam
energies and for normalizing O-18(n,alpha)N-15
yields. The other detectors were mounted on a movable
plate, and subtended a solid angle of approximately
11.1 msr. In the energy range of 550 keV < Ep< 235
keV, a 3.05 micrometer thick Ni foil was placed in
front of each of the four movable counters to stop
the elastically scattered protons. At low proton
energies, charge collection after transmission
through the target foils was found to be unreliable,
probably due to scattering and charge exchange. Hence
the absolute cross sections were deduced from the
W(p,p)W elastic cross sections which were assumed to
be pure Rutherford. The solid angles of the movable
detectors relative to that of the monitor detector
were measured by means of the W(p,p)W reaction at 2
MeV, by placing the detectors, one at a time, at the
same backward angle as the monitor detector. The
results agreed with geometrically estimated values.
Only the measured relative solid angle values
were used in calculating cross sections.
The data were analyzed using the R-matrix theory.
Since the entrance and exit channels have spin and
parity 1/2+ and 1/2-, respectively, for a resonance
with well-defined spin and parity Jpi, only one
l-value is allowed for each channel. The values for
the boundary conditions and the interaction radii are
arbitrary insofar as small changes in their values
can be compensated for by appropriate changes in the
level parameters without affecting the calculated
cross sections. The data were fitted with sums of
Legendre polynomials and the total cross sections
were obtained. In fitting the total cross section,
the contribution from the resonance at E(cm)=314.5
keV was neglected. The level parameters for the 1/2+
resonance at Ep=846 keV and the 3/2- resonance at
Ep=629.5 keV have been determined very accurately by
Yagi et al. and the reported values were used in the
calculation. In addition a broad 1/2+ resonance at
650 keV and a broad 1/2- resonance at 750 keV were
introduced. The parameters of these two resonances
were adjusted to fit the O-18(p,alpha)N-15 cross
section as well as previously published data.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: No explicit procedure is given.
Counting statistics was kept below 10%.
The overall uncertainty in the
experimental values of the products
(Nw/N18)dsigma(theta0)/dsigma9theta1) is estimated to
be 4% or less.

The S-function (factor) is defined by: S=E sigma(E)
exp(2pi/eta), where eta=Z1 Z2 e2/hbar v. Below 300 keV,
this S-function is approximated by: S(E)=S0 + S1E +
1/2S2E2, where S0=46 MeV b, S1 = 13 b and S2 = 160
MeV-1 b.
